{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018xeoKagkHYAyxGDERbRYCq","type":"tool_result","content":"400\thave been proposed to improve RoPE’s ability to handle\n401\tlong sequences, including position interpolation (?) which\n402\trescales positional indices at inference time and YaRN (?)\n403\twhich refines this strategy through frequency-aware scaling\n404\tto improve stability.\n405\t2D RoPE for Vision.Extending RoPE to 2D vision data\n406\trequires careful design choices. The straightforward ap-\n407\tproach, which we term axial 2D RoPE, splits the embedding\n408\tdimension into two halves and applies 1D RoPE indepen-\n409\tdently along the x and y axes. The 2D RoPE method has\n410\tbeen adopted in many vision tasks, such as SAM 2 (?)\n411\tfor image segmentation and Qwen-Image (?) for image\n412\tgeneration. M-RoPE (Multimodal RoPE) (?) decomposes\n413\timage indices into height, width, and temporal components\n414\tto align visual patches with 1D text sequences. However,\n415\tthese axial approaches encode only horizontal and verti-\n416\tcal relationships, without explicit awareness of diagonal\n417\tor other directional spatial patterns. Heo et al. (?) pro-\n418\tposed RoPE-Mixed, treats the frequencies for both spatial\n419\taxes as learnable parameters, allowing the network to adap-\n420\ttively ”mix” axial signals to capture diagonal information.\n421\tIn multimodal settings, several works generalize RoPE to\n422\tjointly handle tokens from different modalities. For instance,\n423\tCircle-RoPE (?) project image token indices onto a ring\n424\tthat is orthogonal to the linear axis of text token indices to\n425\teliminate spurious cross-modal biases.\n426\t3. Method\n427\t3.1. Preliminaries: Rotary Position Embedding\n428\t3.1.1. 1D ROPE\n429\tRotary Position Embedding (?) encodes positional infor-\n430\tmation through rotation operations. Given a d-dimensional\n431\tquery or key vector x∈R d at position m, RoPE applies a\n432\tblock-diagonal rotation matrix:\n433\tRoPE(x, m) =R mx(1)\n434\twhere Rm is a block-diagonal matrix composed of d/2 2D\n435\trotation matrices:\n436\tRm =\n437\t\n438\t\n439\tR(0)\n440\tm\n441\t...\n442\tR(d/2−1)\n443\tm\n444\t\n445\t (2)\n446\twith each2×2block being:\n447\tR(t)\n448\tm =\n449\t\u0012cos(mθt)−sin(mθ t)\n450\tsin(mθt) cos(mθ t)\n451\t\u0013\n452\t(3)\n453\tThe frequency θt is typically set as θt =θ −t/(d/2)\n454\tbase for\n455\tt= 0,1, . . . , d/2−1 , where θbase is the base frequency that\n456\tis commonly set to 10,000. This geometric progression of\n457\tfrequencies allows RoPE to encode positional dependencies\n458\tat multiple scales.\n459\tA key property of RoPE is that the dot product between\n460\trotated vectors depends only on their relative position:\n461\t⟨RoPE(q, m),RoPE(k, n)⟩=q ⊤Rm−nk(4)\n462\tThis property enables RoPE to implicitly encode relative\n463\tpositional information when calculating the attention matrix\n464\tin the self-attention mechanism.\n465\t3\n466\t165\n467\t166\n468\t167\n469\t168\n470\t169\n471\t170\n472\t171\n473\t172\n474\t173\n475\t174\n476\t175\n477\t176\n478\t177\n479\t178\n480\t179\n481\t180\n482\t181\n483\t182\n484\t183\n485\t184\n486\t185\n487\t186\n488\t187\n489\t188\n490\t189\n491\t190\n492\t191\n493\t192\n494\t193\n495\t194\n496\t195\n497\t196\n498\t197\n499\t198\n500\t199\n501\t200\n502\t201\n503\t202\n504\t203\n505\t204\n506\t205\n507\t206\n508\t207\n509\t208\n510\t209\n511\t210\n512\t211\n513\t212\n514\t213\n515\t214\n516\t215\n517\t216\n518\t217\n519\t218\n520\t219\n521\tSpiral RoPE: Rotate Your Rotary Positional Embeddings in the 2D Plane\n522\t3.1.2. AXIAL2D ROPE\n523\tRoPE was originally designed for 1D sequences. For 2D\n524\timages, the standard approach is to extend RoPE by decom-\n525\tposing the spatial position into x and y coordinates. Given\n526\ta patch at position (px, py), the d-dimensional embedding\n527\tx∈R d is split into two halves:\n528\tx(x) = (x0, x1, . . . , xd/2−1)(5)\n529\tx(y) = (xd/2, xd/2+1, . . . , xd−1)(6)\n530\tThe first half is rotated using the x-coordinate, and the sec-\n531\tond half using the y-coordinate:\n532\tRoPE-2D(x, px, py) =\n533\t\u0012Rpx x(x)\n534\tRpy x(y)\n535\t\u0013\n536\t(7)\n537\tThe rotation matricesRpx and Rpy are typically constructed\n538\tusing the same set of frequencies. Each sub-embedding x(x)\n539\tand x(y) has dimensionality d/2 and thus can only accom-\n540\tmodate d/4 distinct rotary frequencies, i.e., half of those\n541\tavailable in the original 1D RoPE.\n542\tDespite the good simplicity of transferring 1D RoPE to\n543\t2D inputs, this axial design only encodes positional rela-\n544\ttionships along the axis-aligned directions, leading to an\n545\tinherent limitation. The x-coordinate and y-coordinate are\n546\tprocessed independently, without any explicit encoding of\n547\tdiagonal or other directional relationships. Consider patches\n548\tat positions p1 = (0,0) and p2 = (1,1) , which are diag-\n549\tonally adjacent. With conventional 2D RoPE, the relative\n550\tposition encoding in the x-dimensions reflects ∆x= 1 , and\n551\tin the y-dimensions reflects ∆y= 1 , but there is no direct\n552\tencoding of the diagonal relationship.\n553\t3.2. Spiral RoPE\n554\tTo address this limitation, we propose to extend 2D RoPE by\n555\tapplying additionalspatial rotationson the 2D panel. For\n556\texample, we can directly encode the diagonal displacement√\n557\t2 along the 45-degree direction, which can provide richer\n558\tpositional information. And more generally, we can encode\n559\tpositions along multiple uniformly distributed directions,\n560\twhich provides the model with a more complete description\n561\tof spatial relationships.\n562\tFormally, let K be the number of directions we want to\n563\tencode. We uniformly distribute K directions in the angular\n564\trange[0, π):\n565\tϕk = kπ\n566\tK , k= 0,1, . . . , K−1(8)\n567\tNote that we only need to cover [0, π) rather than [0,2π)\n568\tbecause directions ϕ and ϕ+π are parallel, and RoPE natu-\n569\trally handles both positive and negative positions through\n570\tits rotation mechanism.\n571\tFor each directionϕ k, we define a unit direction vector:\n572\tuk = (cosϕ k,sinϕ k)(9)\n573\tGiven a patch at 2D position p= (p x, py), we compute its\n574\tprojected position along directionkas:\n575\ttk(p) =p·u k =p x cosϕ k +p y sinϕ k (10)\n576\tWe partition the d-dimensional embedding into K equal\n577\tgroups, each with d/K dimensions. The k-th group, de-\n578\tnotedx (k), is rotated using the projected positiont k:\n579\tSpiral RoPE(x,p) =\n580\t\n581\t\n582\tR(0)\n583\tt0(p)x(0)\n584\tR(1)\n585\tt1(p)x(1)\n586\t...\n587\tR(K−1)\n588\ttK−1 (p)x(K−1)\n589\t\n590\t\n591\t(11)\n592\twhere R(k)\n593\tt denotes the rotation matrix for direction k with\n594\tits specific frequency assignment.\n595\tA critical design choice in Spiral RoPE is how to assign\n596\trotation frequencies θi to different directions. A naive ap-\n597\tproach would independently assignd/(2K)frequencies to\n598\teach direction. However, this limits the number of distinct\n599\tfrequencies as K increases, reducing the model’s ability to\n600\tencode positions at multiple scales.\n601\tTo maximize frequency diversity, we adopt an interleaved\n602\tfrequency assignment strategy. We first compute a pool of\n603\td/4 base frequencies using the same formula as axial 2D\n604\tRoPE:\n605\tθt =θ −t/(d/4)\n606\tbase , t= 0,1, . . . , d/4−1(12)\n607\tThis gives us the same number of distinct frequencies as the\n608\tconventional 2D RoPE baseline.\n609\tTo distribute these frequencies across directions,\n610\twe adopt a grouped interleaved assignment strat-\n611\tegy. We first group adjacent frequencies into pairs:\n612\t(θ0, θ1),(θ 2, θ3), . . . ,(θd/4−2, θd/4−1). We then assign\n613\tthese pairs to direction groups in a round-robin fashion.\n614\tSpecifically, we pair directions that are 90° apart (i.e.,\n615\tperpendicular), since they encode orthogonal spatial\n616\trelationships. For direction pair (k, k+K/2) where\n617\tk < K/2, we assign frequency pairs:\n618\tΘ(k) = Θ(k+K/2) ={θ 2k, θ2k+1, θ2k+K , θ2k+K+1 , . . .}\n619\t(13)\n620\tFor example, with K= 4 directions (0◦, 45◦, 90◦, 135◦)\n621\tandd= 32, the frequency assignment is:\n622\t•θ 0, θ1, θ4, θ5 are assigned to directions 0◦ and 90◦\n623\t4\n624\t220\n625\t221\n626\t222\n627\t223\n628\t224\n629\t225\n630\t226\n631\t227\n632\t228\n633\t229\n634\t230\n635\t231\n636\t232\n637\t233\n638\t234\n639\t235\n640\t236\n641\t237\n642\t238\n643\t239\n644\t240\n645\t241\n646\t242\n647\t243\n648\t244\n649\t245\n650\t246\n651\t247\n652\t248\n653\t249\n654\t250\n655\t251\n656\t252\n657\t253\n658\t254\n659\t255\n660\t256\n661\t257\n662\t258\n663\t259\n664\t260\n665\t261\n666\t262\n667\t263\n668\t264\n669\t265\n670\t266\n671\t267\n672\t268\n673\t269\n674\t270\n675\t271\n676\t272\n677\t273\n678\t274\n679\tSpiral RoPE: Rotate Your Rotary Positional Embeddings in the 2D Plane\n680\t•θ 2, θ3, θ6, θ7 are assigned to directions 45◦ and 135◦\n681\tFigure 1 visualizes the frequency assignment by plotting\n682\teach frequency ±θt as a point in the 2D frequency plane\n683\talong the direction it encodes. For traditional 2D axial\n684\tRoPE, all frequencies lie on the horizontal (0◦) and vertical\n685\t(90◦) axes, corresponding to frequency vectors(±θt,0) and\n686\t(0,±θ t). In contrast, Spiral RoPE with K= 8 distributes\n687\tfrequencies across K/2 = 4 pairs of perpendicular direc-\n688\ttions: 0◦/90◦, 22.5◦/112.5◦, 45◦/135◦, and 67.5◦/157.5◦,\n689\twhich forms aspiralpattern. This visualization illustrates\n690\thow Spiral RoPE expands directional coverage beyond the\n691\tcoordinate axes while maintaining the same total number of\n692\tfrequencies.\n693\tThis grouped interleaved assignment ensures that: (1) we\n694\tutilize all d/4 distinct frequencies, matching the capacity\n695\tof axial 2D RoPE; (2) perpendicular direction pairs share\n696\tthe same frequency set, analogous to how axial 2D RoPE\n697\tuses the same frequencies for both x and y axes; and (3)\n698\teach direction receives a mix of low and high frequencies\n699\tfrom adjacent pairs, enabling multi-scale positional encod-\n700\ting within each direction.\n701\tSpiral RoPE preserves the relative position encoding prop-\n702\terty of RoPE: for patches at positions p and p′, since\n703\ttk(p)−t k(p′) =t k(p−p ′), the attention score contri-\n704\tbution depends only on the relative position p−p ′. Fur-\n705\tthermore, by uniformly distributing directional encodings,\n706\tSpiral RoPE provides more isotropic spatial awareness com-\n707\tpared to axial 2D RoPE, which treats horizontal and vertical\n708\tdirections preferentially. Note that Spiral RoPE can be im-\n709\tplemented efficiently by precomputing the rotation matrices\n710\tfor all positions and directions, with minimal computational\n711\toverhead compared to axial 2D RoPE.\n712\tTo further illustrate the representation power of Spiral RoPE,\n713\twe perform a 2D Fourier analysis comparing axial 2D RoPE\n714\twith Spiral RoPE. We consider d= 1024 , which yields\n715\td/4 = 256 distinct RoPE frequencies. Given a binary im-\n716\tage, we first apply 2D FFT to obtain its frequency-domain\n717\trepresentation. We then retain only the frequency compo-\n718\tnents that can be represented by each RoPE variant: for\n719\taxial 2D RoPE, we keep frequencies along the horizontal\n720\tand vertical axes(±θt,0) and (0,±θ t); for Spiral RoPE, we\n721\tkeep frequencies along all K= 8 directions as illustrated\n722\tin Figure 1. All other frequency components are masked to\n723\tzero. Finally, we apply 2D iFFT to reconstruct the image\n724\tand compare the result with the original input. Figure 2\n725\tshows the reconstruction results for two input images: a\n726\tsingle point and a circle on the 64×64 grid. The axial 2D\n727\tRoPE reconstruction exhibits visible artifacts along the hor-\n728\tizontal and vertical axes, as it can only represent frequency\n729\tcomponents in these two directions. In contrast, Spiral\n730\tRoPE produces reconstructions that are closer to the orig-\n731\tinal images, demonstrating its ability to capture a broader\n732\trange of spatial patterns through multi-directional frequency\n733\tcoverage.\n734\t4. Experiments\n735\tWe conduct comprehensive experiments to validate the ef-\n736\tfectiveness of Spiral RoPE across multiple vision tasks:\n737\timage classification on ImageNet-1k, semantic segmenta-\n738\ttion on ADE20k, and class-conditional image generation on\n739\tImageNet. Our experiments demonstrate that Spiral RoPE\n740\tconsistently improves performance over baselines and prior\n741\t2D RoPE methods.\n742\t4.1. Image Classification\n743\tSetup.We evaluate Spiral RoPE on ImageNet-1k (?) clas-\n744\tsification using DeiT (?) as the base architecture. We train\n745\tDeiT-Small, DeiT-Base and DeiT-Large models with and\n746\twithout Spiral RoPE on three target resolutions: 224×224 ,\n747\t384×384 , and 448×448 . Following (?), we combine Spi-\n748\tral RoPE with the original absolute positional embedding\n749\t(APE), as this combination has been shown to be effective."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e05e2ee8-2a48-4730-8e68-8246ab911fe5","uuid":"39b39a4c-fac6-4be6-afce-bcab016fd864","timestamp":"2026-04-26T19:34:19.257Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/papers/spiralrope.txt","content":"have been proposed to improve RoPE’s ability to handle\nlong sequences, including position interpolation (?) which\nrescales positional indices at inference time and YaRN (?)\nwhich refines this strategy through frequency-aware scaling\nto improve stability.\n2D RoPE for Vision.Extending RoPE to 2D vision data\nrequires careful design choices. The straightforward ap-\nproach, which we term axial 2D RoPE, splits the embedding\ndimension into two halves and applies 1D RoPE indepen-\ndently along the x and y axes. The 2D RoPE method has\nbeen adopted in many vision tasks, such as SAM 2 (?)\nfor image segmentation and Qwen-Image (?) for image\ngeneration. M-RoPE (Multimodal RoPE) (?) decomposes\nimage indices into height, width, and temporal components\nto align visual patches with 1D text sequences. However,\nthese axial approaches encode only horizontal and verti-\ncal relationships, without explicit awareness of diagonal\nor other directional spatial patterns. Heo et al. (?) pro-\nposed RoPE-Mixed, treats the frequencies for both spatial\naxes as learnable parameters, allowing the network to adap-\ntively ”mix” axial signals to capture diagonal information.\nIn multimodal settings, several works generalize RoPE to\njointly handle tokens from different modalities. For instance,\nCircle-RoPE (?) project image token indices onto a ring\nthat is orthogonal to the linear axis of text token indices to\neliminate spurious cross-modal biases.\n3. Method\n3.1. Preliminaries: Rotary Position Embedding\n3.1.1. 1D ROPE\nRotary Position Embedding (?) encodes positional infor-\nmation through rotation operations. Given a d-dimensional\nquery or key vector x∈R d at position m, RoPE applies a\nblock-diagonal rotation matrix:\nRoPE(x, m) =R mx(1)\nwhere Rm is a block-diagonal matrix composed of d/2 2D\nrotation matrices:\nRm =\n\n\nR(0)\nm\n...\nR(d/2−1)\nm\n\n (2)\nwith each2×2block being:\nR(t)\nm =\n\u0012cos(mθt)−sin(mθ t)\nsin(mθt) cos(mθ t)\n\u0013\n(3)\nThe frequency θt is typically set as θt =θ −t/(d/2)\nbase for\nt= 0,1, . . . , d/2−1 , where θbase is the base frequency that\nis commonly set to 10,000. This geometric progression of\nfrequencies allows RoPE to encode positional dependencies\nat multiple scales.\nA key property of RoPE is that the dot product between\nrotated vectors depends only on their relative position:\n⟨RoPE(q, m),RoPE(k, n)⟩=q ⊤Rm−nk(4)\nThis property enables RoPE to implicitly encode relative\npositional information when calculating the attention matrix\nin the self-attention mechanism.\n3\n165\n166\n167\n168\n169\n170\n171\n172\n173\n174\n175\n176\n177\n178\n179\n180\n181\n182\n183\n184\n185\n186\n187\n188\n189\n190\n191\n192\n193\n194\n195\n196\n197\n198\n199\n200\n201\n202\n203\n204\n205\n206\n207\n208\n209\n210\n211\n212\n213\n214\n215\n216\n217\n218\n219\nSpiral RoPE: Rotate Your Rotary Positional Embeddings in the 2D Plane\n3.1.2. AXIAL2D ROPE\nRoPE was originally designed for 1D sequences. For 2D\nimages, the standard approach is to extend RoPE by decom-\nposing the spatial position into x and y coordinates. Given\na patch at position (px, py), the d-dimensional embedding\nx∈R d is split into two halves:\nx(x) = (x0, x1, . . . , xd/2−1)(5)\nx(y) = (xd/2, xd/2+1, . . . , xd−1)(6)\nThe first half is rotated using the x-coordinate, and the sec-\nond half using the y-coordinate:\nRoPE-2D(x, px, py) =\n\u0012Rpx x(x)\nRpy x(y)\n\u0013\n(7)\nThe rotation matricesRpx and Rpy are typically constructed\nusing the same set of frequencies. Each sub-embedding x(x)\nand x(y) has dimensionality d/2 and thus can only accom-\nmodate d/4 distinct rotary frequencies, i.e., half of those\navailable in the original 1D RoPE.\nDespite the good simplicity of transferring 1D RoPE to\n2D inputs, this axial design only encodes positional rela-\ntionships along the axis-aligned directions, leading to an\ninherent limitation. The x-coordinate and y-coordinate are\nprocessed independently, without any explicit encoding of\ndiagonal or other directional relationships. Consider patches\nat positions p1 = (0,0) and p2 = (1,1) , which are diag-\nonally adjacent. With conventional 2D RoPE, the relative\nposition encoding in the x-dimensions reflects ∆x= 1 , and\nin the y-dimensions reflects ∆y= 1 , but there is no direct\nencoding of the diagonal relationship.\n3.2. Spiral RoPE\nTo address this limitation, we propose to extend 2D RoPE by\napplying additionalspatial rotationson the 2D panel. For\nexample, we can directly encode the diagonal displacement√\n2 along the 45-degree direction, which can provide richer\npositional information. And more generally, we can encode\npositions along multiple uniformly distributed directions,\nwhich provides the model with a more complete description\nof spatial relationships.\nFormally, let K be the number of directions we want to\nencode. We uniformly distribute K directions in the angular\nrange[0, π):\nϕk = kπ\nK , k= 0,1, . . . , K−1(8)\nNote that we only need to cover [0, π) rather than [0,2π)\nbecause directions ϕ and ϕ+π are parallel, and RoPE natu-\nrally handles both positive and negative positions through\nits rotation mechanism.\nFor each directionϕ k, we define a unit direction vector:\nuk = (cosϕ k,sinϕ k)(9)\nGiven a patch at 2D position p= (p x, py), we compute its\nprojected position along directionkas:\ntk(p) =p·u k =p x cosϕ k +p y sinϕ k (10)\nWe partition the d-dimensional embedding into K equal\ngroups, each with d/K dimensions. The k-th group, de-\nnotedx (k), is rotated using the projected positiont k:\nSpiral RoPE(x,p) =\n\n\nR(0)\nt0(p)x(0)\nR(1)\nt1(p)x(1)\n...\nR(K−1)\ntK−1 (p)x(K−1)\n\n\n(11)\nwhere R(k)\nt denotes the rotation matrix for direction k with\nits specific frequency assignment.\nA critical design choice in Spiral RoPE is how to assign\nrotation frequencies θi to different directions. A naive ap-\nproach would independently assignd/(2K)frequencies to\neach direction. However, this limits the number of distinct\nfrequencies as K increases, reducing the model’s ability to\nencode positions at multiple scales.\nTo maximize frequency diversity, we adopt an interleaved\nfrequency assignment strategy. We first compute a pool of\nd/4 base frequencies using the same formula as axial 2D\nRoPE:\nθt =θ −t/(d/4)\nbase , t= 0,1, . . . , d/4−1(12)\nThis gives us the same number of distinct frequencies as the\nconventional 2D RoPE baseline.\nTo distribute these frequencies across directions,\nwe adopt a grouped interleaved assignment strat-\negy. We first group adjacent frequencies into pairs:\n(θ0, θ1),(θ 2, θ3), . . . ,(θd/4−2, θd/4−1). We then assign\nthese pairs to direction groups in a round-robin fashion.\nSpecifically, we pair directions that are 90° apart (i.e.,\nperpendicular), since they encode orthogonal spatial\nrelationships. For direction pair (k, k+K/2) where\nk < K/2, we assign frequency pairs:\nΘ(k) = Θ(k+K/2) ={θ 2k, θ2k+1, θ2k+K , θ2k+K+1 , . . .}\n(13)\nFor example, with K= 4 directions (0◦, 45◦, 90◦, 135◦)\nandd= 32, the frequency assignment is:\n•θ 0, θ1, θ4, θ5 are assigned to directions 0◦ and 90◦\n4\n220\n221\n222\n223\n224\n225\n226\n227\n228\n229\n230\n231\n232\n233\n234\n235\n236\n237\n238\n239\n240\n241\n242\n243\n244\n245\n246\n247\n248\n249\n250\n251\n252\n253\n254\n255\n256\n257\n258\n259\n260\n261\n262\n263\n264\n265\n266\n267\n268\n269\n270\n271\n272\n273\n274\nSpiral RoPE: Rotate Your Rotary Positional Embeddings in the 2D Plane\n•θ 2, θ3, θ6, θ7 are assigned to directions 45◦ and 135◦\nFigure 1 visualizes the frequency assignment by plotting\neach frequency ±θt as a point in the 2D frequency plane\nalong the direction it encodes. For traditional 2D axial\nRoPE, all frequencies lie on the horizontal (0◦) and vertical\n(90◦) axes, corresponding to frequency vectors(±θt,0) and\n(0,±θ t). In contrast, Spiral RoPE with K= 8 distributes\nfrequencies across K/2 = 4 pairs of perpendicular direc-\ntions: 0◦/90◦, 22.5◦/112.5◦, 45◦/135◦, and 67.5◦/157.5◦,\nwhich forms aspiralpattern. This visualization illustrates\nhow Spiral RoPE expands directional coverage beyond the\ncoordinate axes while maintaining the same total number of\nfrequencies.\nThis grouped interleaved assignment ensures that: (1) we\nutilize all d/4 distinct frequencies, matching the capacity\nof axial 2D RoPE; (2) perpendicular direction pairs share\nthe same frequency set, analogous to how axial 2D RoPE\nuses the same frequencies for both x and y axes; and (3)\neach direction receives a mix of low and high frequencies\nfrom adjacent pairs, enabling multi-scale positional encod-\ning within each direction.\nSpiral RoPE preserves the relative position encoding prop-\nerty of RoPE: for patches at positions p and p′, since\ntk(p)−t k(p′) =t k(p−p ′), the attention score contri-\nbution depends only on the relative position p−p ′. Fur-\nthermore, by uniformly distributing directional encodings,\nSpiral RoPE provides more isotropic spatial awareness com-\npared to axial 2D RoPE, which treats horizontal and vertical\ndirections preferentially. Note that Spiral RoPE can be im-\nplemented efficiently by precomputing the rotation matrices\nfor all positions and directions, with minimal computational\noverhead compared to axial 2D RoPE.\nTo further illustrate the representation power of Spiral RoPE,\nwe perform a 2D Fourier analysis comparing axial 2D RoPE\nwith Spiral RoPE. We consider d= 1024 , which yields\nd/4 = 256 distinct RoPE frequencies. Given a binary im-\nage, we first apply 2D FFT to obtain its frequency-domain\nrepresentation. We then retain only the frequency compo-\nnents that can be represented by each RoPE variant: for\naxial 2D RoPE, we keep frequencies along the horizontal\nand vertical axes(±θt,0) and (0,±θ t); for Spiral RoPE, we\nkeep frequencies along all K= 8 directions as illustrated\nin Figure 1. All other frequency components are masked to\nzero. Finally, we apply 2D iFFT to reconstruct the image\nand compare the result with the original input. Figure 2\nshows the reconstruction results for two input images: a\nsingle point and a circle on the 64×64 grid. The axial 2D\nRoPE reconstruction exhibits visible artifacts along the hor-\nizontal and vertical axes, as it can only represent frequency\ncomponents in these two directions. In contrast, Spiral\nRoPE produces reconstructions that are closer to the orig-\ninal images, demonstrating its ability to capture a broader\nrange of spatial patterns through multi-directional frequency\ncoverage.\n4. Experiments\nWe conduct comprehensive experiments to validate the ef-\nfectiveness of Spiral RoPE across multiple vision tasks:\nimage classification on ImageNet-1k, semantic segmenta-\ntion on ADE20k, and class-conditional image generation on\nImageNet. Our experiments demonstrate that Spiral RoPE\nconsistently improves performance over baselines and prior\n2D RoPE methods.\n4.1. Image Classification\nSetup.We evaluate Spiral RoPE on ImageNet-1k (?) clas-\nsification using DeiT (?) as the base architecture. We train\nDeiT-Small, DeiT-Base and DeiT-Large models with and\nwithout Spiral RoPE on three target resolutions: 224×224 ,\n384×384 , and 448×448 . Following (?), we combine Spi-\nral RoPE with the original absolute positional embedding\n(APE), as this combination has been shown to be effective.","numLines":350,"startLine":400,"totalLines":1705}}}
