{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FWANE35KRVRGoH2JYKjsUp","type":"tool_result","content":"1170\t5.2. Ablation Studies\n1171\tWe conduct ablation studies on the ImageNet-1k classifica-\n1172\ttion task using DeiT-Base at224×224 resolution to analyze\n1173\tthe effect of key hyperparameters in Spiral RoPE. All abla-\n1174\ttion experiments use the same training recipe as described\n1175\tin Section 4.1, with evaluation using the final checkpoint\n1176\twith EMA weights and full crop.\n1177\tNumber of Directions K.We first ablate the number\n1178\tof directions K in Spiral RoPE with the frequency scal-\n1179\ting factor fixed at 1.5. As shown in Table 5, Spiral RoPE\n1180\tconsistently outperforms the axial RoPE baseline (83.31%)\n1181\tacross all values of K. Increasing K from 4 to 16 gradually\n1182\timproves accuracy, with K= 16 achieving the best per-\n1183\tformance (83.39%). However, further increasing K to 32\n1184\tslightly degrades performance (83.32%), suggesting that ex-\n1185\tcessive directional partitioning may reduce the embedding\n1186\tTable 5.Ablation on the number\n1187\tof directionsK.\n1188\tKACC(%)\n1189\t2 (AXIALROPE) 83.31\n1190\t4 83.31\n1191\t8 83.34\n1192\t1683.39\n1193\t32 83.32\n1194\tTable 6.Ablation on the fre-\n1195\tquency scaling factor.\n1196\tSCALEACC(%)\n1197\t1.00 83.33\n1198\t1.25 83.13\n1199\t1.5083.39\n1200\t1.75 83.34\n1201\t2.00 83.23\n1202\tcapacity per direction without providing additional benefit.\n1203\tBased on these results, we select K= 16 as the default\n1204\tconfiguration for our classification experiments.\n1205\tFrequency Scaling Factor.We also ablate the frequency\n1206\tscaling factor that multiplies all base frequenciesθt in Spiral\n1207\tRoPE, with K fixed at 16. As shown in Table 6, the scaling\n1208\tfactor has a notable impact on performance. A scaling factor\n1209\tof 1.0 (no scaling) achieves 83.33%, while increasing to 1.5\n1210\tyields the best result (83.39%). However, larger scaling\n1211\tfactors (1.75, 2.0) lead to decreased performance, likely\n1212\tbecause excessively high frequencies cause the rotations to\n1213\tvary too rapidly across positions, making it difficult for the\n1214\tmodel to learn stable positional relationships. We select 1.5\n1215\tas the default scaling factor for our experiments.\n1216\t6. Conclusion\n1217\tWe have presented Spiral RoPE, a simple yet effective exten-\n1218\tsion of rotary position embedding for vision transformers\n1219\tthat addresses the directional constraint of conventional Ax-\n1220\tial 2D RoPE by distributing positional encoding across K\n1221\tuniformly spaced directions. Extensive experiments across\n1222\timage classification, semantic segmentation, and image gen-\n1223\teration demonstrate consistent performance improvements,\n1224\twith particularly strong resolution extrapolation capability.\n1225\tThese results suggest that directional diversity in positional\n1226\tencoding plays a critical role in modeling 2D spatial rela-\n1227\ttionships, and that modest geometric extensions to rotary\n1228\tembeddings can substantially enhance spatial representation\n1229\tin vision transformers.\n1230\t8\n1231\t440\n1232\t441\n1233\t442\n1234\t443\n1235\t444\n1236\t445\n1237\t446\n1238\t447\n1239\t448\n1240\t449\n1241\t450\n1242\t451\n1243\t452\n1244\t453\n1245\t454\n1246\t455\n1247\t456\n1248\t457\n1249\t458\n1250\t459\n1251\t460\n1252\t461\n1253\t462\n1254\t463\n1255\t464\n1256\t465\n1257\t466\n1258\t467\n1259\t468\n1260\t469\n1261\t470\n1262\t471\n1263\t472\n1264\t473\n1265\t474\n1266\t475\n1267\t476\n1268\t477\n1269\t478\n1270\t479\n1271\t480\n1272\t481\n1273\t482\n1274\t483\n1275\t484\n1276\t485\n1277\t486\n1278\t487\n1279\t488\n1280\t489\n1281\t490\n1282\t491\n1283\t492\n1284\t493\n1285\t494\n1286\tSpiral RoPE: Rotate Your Rotary Positional Embeddings in the 2D Plane\n1287\tA. Implementation Details\n1288\tA.1. Image Classification\n1289\tPre-training.We train DeiT models on ImageNet-1K following an improved training recipe. For DeiT-Base and DeiT-\n1290\tSmall, we train for 300 epochs with a batch size of 4096, learning rate of 2×10 −4, weight decay of 0.3, and drop path\n1291\trate of 0.1. For DeiT-Large, we train for 200 epochs with the same hyperparameters except drop path rate of 0.2. We use\n1292\tAdamW optimizer with β1 = 0.95 and cosine learning rate schedule with 20 warmup epochs. We employ the same data\n1293\taugmentation pipeline during training as the original DeiT implementation.\n1294\tFine-tuning.For fine-tuning at 224×224 , we train for 20 epochs with learning rate 10−5, weight decay 0.1, and the\n1295\tsame drop path rate as pre-training. For higher resolutions (384×384 and 448×448 ), we fine-tune from the 224×224\n1296\tcheckpoint for 20 epochs with the same hyperparameters. We use full crop (crop ratio 1.0) during evaluation.\n1297\tSpiral RoPE Configuration.For all classification experiments, we use K= 16 directions with base frequency scaling\n1298\tfactor 1.5 (i.e.,θ base = 15000). Spiral RoPE is combined with the original absolute positional embedding (APE).\n1299\tTable 7.Pre-training hyperparameters for ImageNet-1K classification.\n1300\tHyperparameter DeiT-Base and DeiT-Small DeiT-Large\n1301\tEpochs 300 200\n1302\tBatch size 4096 4096\n1303\tOptimizer AdamW AdamW\n1304\tLearning rate2×10 −4 2×10 −4\n1305\tWeight decay 0.3 0.3\n1306\tβ1,β 2 0.95, 0.999 0.95, 0.999\n1307\tLR schedule Cosine Cosine\n1308\tWarmup epochs 20 20\n1309\tDrop path 0.1 0.2\n1310\tLabel smoothing 0.1 0.1\n1311\tData Augmentation\n1312\tRandAugment (9, 0.5) (9, 0.5)\n1313\tMixupα0.8 0.8\n1314\tCutMixα1.0 1.0\n1315\tRandom erasing 0.25 0.25\n1316\tSpiral RoPE Parameters\n1317\tNumber of directions (K) 16 16\n1318\tBase frequency scale 1.5 1.5\n1319\tA.2. Semantic Segmentation\n1320\tWe use UperNet as the segmentation framework with DeiT backbones initialized from ImageNet pre-trained weights at\n1321\t224×224 resolution. Models are trained on ADE20K at 512×512 resolution for 160K iterations with a total batch size\n1322\tof 16 (8 GPUs × 2 samples per GPU). We use AdamW optimizer with learning rate 6×10 −5, weight decay 0.01, and\n1323\tpolynomial learning rate decay with 1.5K warmup iterations. Weight decay is disabled for position embeddings, class\n1324\ttokens, normalization layers, and layer scale parameters. For Spiral RoPE models, we use the same K= 16 and base\n1325\tfrequency scale 1.5 as in classification.\n1326\tA.3. Image Generation\n1327\tWe follow the training recipe of the original DiT implementation (?). Specifically, we train DiT models on ImageNet\n1328\t256×256 for class-conditional image generation. All models are trained for 400K steps with a global batch size of 256.\n1329\t9\n1330\t495\n1331\t496\n1332\t497\n1333\t498\n1334\t499\n1335\t500\n1336\t501\n1337\t502\n1338\t503\n1339\t504\n1340\t505\n1341\t506\n1342\t507\n1343\t508\n1344\t509\n1345\t510\n1346\t511\n1347\t512\n1348\t513\n1349\t514\n1350\t515\n1351\t516\n1352\t517\n1353\t518\n1354\t519\n1355\t520\n1356\t521\n1357\t522\n1358\t523\n1359\t524\n1360\t525\n1361\t526\n1362\t527\n1363\t528\n1364\t529\n1365\t530\n1366\t531\n1367\t532\n1368\t533\n1369\t534"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e05e2ee8-2a48-4730-8e68-8246ab911fe5","uuid":"def3e8c1-4e1a-4630-93be-cac90ea80c89","timestamp":"2026-04-26T19:34:31.973Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/papers/spiralrope.txt","content":"5.2. Ablation Studies\nWe conduct ablation studies on the ImageNet-1k classifica-\ntion task using DeiT-Base at224×224 resolution to analyze\nthe effect of key hyperparameters in Spiral RoPE. All abla-\ntion experiments use the same training recipe as described\nin Section 4.1, with evaluation using the final checkpoint\nwith EMA weights and full crop.\nNumber of Directions K.We first ablate the number\nof directions K in Spiral RoPE with the frequency scal-\ning factor fixed at 1.5. As shown in Table 5, Spiral RoPE\nconsistently outperforms the axial RoPE baseline (83.31%)\nacross all values of K. Increasing K from 4 to 16 gradually\nimproves accuracy, with K= 16 achieving the best per-\nformance (83.39%). However, further increasing K to 32\nslightly degrades performance (83.32%), suggesting that ex-\ncessive directional partitioning may reduce the embedding\nTable 5.Ablation on the number\nof directionsK.\nKACC(%)\n2 (AXIALROPE) 83.31\n4 83.31\n8 83.34\n1683.39\n32 83.32\nTable 6.Ablation on the fre-\nquency scaling factor.\nSCALEACC(%)\n1.00 83.33\n1.25 83.13\n1.5083.39\n1.75 83.34\n2.00 83.23\ncapacity per direction without providing additional benefit.\nBased on these results, we select K= 16 as the default\nconfiguration for our classification experiments.\nFrequency Scaling Factor.We also ablate the frequency\nscaling factor that multiplies all base frequenciesθt in Spiral\nRoPE, with K fixed at 16. As shown in Table 6, the scaling\nfactor has a notable impact on performance. A scaling factor\nof 1.0 (no scaling) achieves 83.33%, while increasing to 1.5\nyields the best result (83.39%). However, larger scaling\nfactors (1.75, 2.0) lead to decreased performance, likely\nbecause excessively high frequencies cause the rotations to\nvary too rapidly across positions, making it difficult for the\nmodel to learn stable positional relationships. We select 1.5\nas the default scaling factor for our experiments.\n6. Conclusion\nWe have presented Spiral RoPE, a simple yet effective exten-\nsion of rotary position embedding for vision transformers\nthat addresses the directional constraint of conventional Ax-\nial 2D RoPE by distributing positional encoding across K\nuniformly spaced directions. Extensive experiments across\nimage classification, semantic segmentation, and image gen-\neration demonstrate consistent performance improvements,\nwith particularly strong resolution extrapolation capability.\nThese results suggest that directional diversity in positional\nencoding plays a critical role in modeling 2D spatial rela-\ntionships, and that modest geometric extensions to rotary\nembeddings can substantially enhance spatial representation\nin vision transformers.\n8\n440\n441\n442\n443\n444\n445\n446\n447\n448\n449\n450\n451\n452\n453\n454\n455\n456\n457\n458\n459\n460\n461\n462\n463\n464\n465\n466\n467\n468\n469\n470\n471\n472\n473\n474\n475\n476\n477\n478\n479\n480\n481\n482\n483\n484\n485\n486\n487\n488\n489\n490\n491\n492\n493\n494\nSpiral RoPE: Rotate Your Rotary Positional Embeddings in the 2D Plane\nA. Implementation Details\nA.1. Image Classification\nPre-training.We train DeiT models on ImageNet-1K following an improved training recipe. For DeiT-Base and DeiT-\nSmall, we train for 300 epochs with a batch size of 4096, learning rate of 2×10 −4, weight decay of 0.3, and drop path\nrate of 0.1. For DeiT-Large, we train for 200 epochs with the same hyperparameters except drop path rate of 0.2. We use\nAdamW optimizer with β1 = 0.95 and cosine learning rate schedule with 20 warmup epochs. We employ the same data\naugmentation pipeline during training as the original DeiT implementation.\nFine-tuning.For fine-tuning at 224×224 , we train for 20 epochs with learning rate 10−5, weight decay 0.1, and the\nsame drop path rate as pre-training. For higher resolutions (384×384 and 448×448 ), we fine-tune from the 224×224\ncheckpoint for 20 epochs with the same hyperparameters. We use full crop (crop ratio 1.0) during evaluation.\nSpiral RoPE Configuration.For all classification experiments, we use K= 16 directions with base frequency scaling\nfactor 1.5 (i.e.,θ base = 15000). Spiral RoPE is combined with the original absolute positional embedding (APE).\nTable 7.Pre-training hyperparameters for ImageNet-1K classification.\nHyperparameter DeiT-Base and DeiT-Small DeiT-Large\nEpochs 300 200\nBatch size 4096 4096\nOptimizer AdamW AdamW\nLearning rate2×10 −4 2×10 −4\nWeight decay 0.3 0.3\nβ1,β 2 0.95, 0.999 0.95, 0.999\nLR schedule Cosine Cosine\nWarmup epochs 20 20\nDrop path 0.1 0.2\nLabel smoothing 0.1 0.1\nData Augmentation\nRandAugment (9, 0.5) (9, 0.5)\nMixupα0.8 0.8\nCutMixα1.0 1.0\nRandom erasing 0.25 0.25\nSpiral RoPE Parameters\nNumber of directions (K) 16 16\nBase frequency scale 1.5 1.5\nA.2. Semantic Segmentation\nWe use UperNet as the segmentation framework with DeiT backbones initialized from ImageNet pre-trained weights at\n224×224 resolution. Models are trained on ADE20K at 512×512 resolution for 160K iterations with a total batch size\nof 16 (8 GPUs × 2 samples per GPU). We use AdamW optimizer with learning rate 6×10 −5, weight decay 0.01, and\npolynomial learning rate decay with 1.5K warmup iterations. Weight decay is disabled for position embeddings, class\ntokens, normalization layers, and layer scale parameters. For Spiral RoPE models, we use the same K= 16 and base\nfrequency scale 1.5 as in classification.\nA.3. Image Generation\nWe follow the training recipe of the original DiT implementation (?). Specifically, we train DiT models on ImageNet\n256×256 for class-conditional image generation. All models are trained for 400K steps with a global batch size of 256.\n9\n495\n496\n497\n498\n499\n500\n501\n502\n503\n504\n505\n506\n507\n508\n509\n510\n511\n512\n513\n514\n515\n516\n517\n518\n519\n520\n521\n522\n523\n524\n525\n526\n527\n528\n529\n530\n531\n532\n533\n534","numLines":200,"startLine":1170,"totalLines":1705}}}
